1490–Male":"1490–Overleden","1425–1492":"1425–1492","1428–Female":"1428–Overleden","1450":"1450","1460":"1460","1492":"1492","1490":"1490","after 1489":"na 1489","1425":"1425","1458":"1458","1457":"1457","1489":"1489","1544":"1544","1500":"1500","1477":"1477","1455":"1455","1487":"1487","1486":"1486","1540":"1540","1452":"1452","1428":"1428","1515":"1515","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Calverley, Yorkshire, England":"Calverley, Yorkshire, England","Leeds, Yorkshire, England":"Leeds, Yorkshire, England","Thornhill, Yorkshire, England":"Thornhill, Yorkshire, England"},"en":{"1460–after 1489":"1460–after 1489","1450–1500":"1450–1500","1452–1492":"1452–1492","1457–1544":"1457–1544","1458–Female":"1458–Deceased","1460–1489":"1460–1489","1455–1515":"1455–1515","1477–Female":"1477–Deceased","1487–1540":"1487–1540","1490–Male":"1490–Deceased","1425–1492":"1425–1492","1428–Female":"1428–Deceased","1450":"1450","1460":"1460","1492":"1492","1490":"1490","after 1489":"after 1489","1425":"1425","1458":"1458","1457":"1457","1489":"1489","1544":"1544","1500":"1500","1477":"1477","1455":"1455","1487":"1487","1486":"1486","1540":"1540","1452":"1452","1428":"1428","1515":"1515","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","Calverley, Yorkshire, England":"Calverley, Yorkshire, England","Leeds, Yorkshire, England":"Leeds, Yorkshire, England","Thornhill, Yorkshire, England":"Thornhill, Yorkshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Amias","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Norman, English: locative name from the French city of Amiens (Somme), which is recorded as  <i>Samarobriva Ambianorum</i> in classical sources.  <i>Samarobriva</i> is a Celtic place-name meaning ‘the bridge over the river Somme’, while the affix  <i>Ambianorum</i> means ‘of the Ambiani’.  <i>Ambiāni</i> is an ethnic name deriving from Celtic  <i>ambi(o)-</i> ‘around’, probably meaning ‘those on both sides (of the Somme)’ or possibly ‘the people of the world’. The affix has replaced the place-name which it once qualified, and it is the ablative form  <i>Ambiānis</i> of this ethnic name which is the source of the current place-name Amiens. For the development of the surname in England, compare ‘merchants of  <i>Amias</i>’, 1326 in   London Letter Books   E (London)."],"variants":[{"name":"Ames","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): from the Old French personal name <i>Amis</i> or from the feminine form, <i>Amice</i>. The Old French word <i>amis</i>, is from Latin <i>amicus</i> ‘friend’, which was used in Late Latin as a term for a man of the lower classes, in particular a slave. There were also derivatives of this as personal names, in particular masculine <i>Amicius</i> and feminine <i>Amicia</i>. Both were in use as personal names in England and may have contributed to the surname.","German: perhaps a nickname for an active person, from an ancient Germanic word related to Old High German <i>amazzig</i> ‘busy’.","Dutch: possibly a patronymic from <i>Ame</i> a common personal name in Holland and Friesland, an abbreviated form of an ancient Germanic personal name, perhaps beginning with <i>amel</i> ‘strong’."]},{"name":"London Letter Books","meanings":["English: (i) occupational name, nickname from Middle English, Anglo-Norman French  <i>bourdour</i>,  <i>bordere</i> ‘jester, joker, buffoon’. (ii) status name from Middle English  <i>border(e)</i> ‘bordar, cottager’ (Old French  <i>bordier</i>, Latin  <i>bordarius</i>), a feudal tenant of the lowest rank. (iii) occupational name perhaps, as Reaney suggests, from an unrecorded Middle English * <i>border</i> ‘maker of boards or tables’. Compare Robert Bordmakere, 1356 in   London Letter Books   G; William  <i>le Bordhewere</i>, 1327 in   Fransson  ; Richard Bordwreghte, 1332 in   Subsidy Rolls   (Sussex)."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Margaret Amias was born in 1460, in Leeds, Yorkshire, England, her father, Percival Amias, was 35 and her mother, Agnes de Lacy, was 32. She married John Drakes in 1486, in Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 2 daughters. She died after 1489, in Calverley, Yorkshire, England."},"et":{"1460–after 1489":"1460–pärast 1489","1450–1500":"1450–1500","1452–1492":"1452–1492","1457–1544":"1457–1544","1458–Female":"1458–Surnud","1460–1489":"1460–1489","1455–1515":"1455–1515","1477–Female":"1477–Surnud","1487–1540":"1487–1540","1490–Male":"1490–Surnud","1425–1492":"1425–1492","1428–Female":"1428–Surnud","1450":"1450","1460":"1460","1492":"1492","1490":"1490","after 1489":"pärast 1489","1425":"1425","1458":"1458","1457":"1457","1489":"1489","1544":"1544","1500":"1500","1477":"1477","1455":"1455","1487":"1487","1486":"1486","1540":"1540","1452":"1452","1428":"1428","1515":"1515","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Calverley, Yorkshire, England":"Calverley, Yorkshire, England","Leeds, Yorkshire, England":"Leeds, Yorkshire, England","Thornhill, Yorkshire, England":"Thornhill, Yorkshire, England"},"fi":{"1460–after 1489":"1460–1489 jälkeen","1450–1500":"1450–1500","1452–1492":"1452–1492","1457–1544":"1457–1544","1458–Female":"1458–Kuollut","1460–1489":"1460–1489","1455–1515":"1455–1515","1477–Female":"1477–Kuollut","1487–1540":"1487–1540","1490–Male":"1490–Kuollut","1425–1492":"1425–1492","1428–Female":"1428–Kuollut","1450":"1450","1460":"1460","1492":"1492","1490":"1490","after 1489":"1489 jälkeen","1425":"1425","1458":"1458","1457":"1457","1489":"1489","1544":"1544","1500":"1500","1477":"1477","1455":"1455","1487":"1487","1486":"1486","1540":"1540","1452":"145